<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-272-066 </DOCNO><DOCID>08 147 202</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Desktop Publishing  Feb 5 1990 v4 n6 p42(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OSF eyes proposal from heavies. (Open Software Foundation) (TheLatest Word) (column)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Product:   DEcorum (Computer program) (design and construction).andO;Topic:     Operating SystemsStandardsIntegrated Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>OSF eyes proposal from Unix heavies Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Locus and Transarchave submitted a proposal to the Open Software Foundation (OSF) to provide anintegrated set of software components for distributed multivendor networkedenvironments.andP;  The proposal also includes components in whose developmentMicrosoft and Digital Equipment participated.andM;Called DEcorum, the submission consists of &quot;technologies that provide auniform architecture for distributed computing,&quot; according to a Transarcspokesperson.andP;  A few of the salient features of DEcorum include:andM;* Remote procedure calls, based on Apollo's Network Computing Architectureand Digital's Network Computing System;andM;* Process transparency, provided by IBM and Locus;andM;* A distributed file system, based on Transarc's AFS (formerly Andrew FileSystem);andM;* Threading facilities, including a threading library based on the proposedPosix threading standard;andM;* PC and Unix connectivity services, based on LAN Manager.andM;There are other features, too, such as services relating to time, directoriesand names, authorization and authentication, administration and distributedaccess to remote devices.andM;What is really significant is that virtually all of the major OSF playershave participated in this proposal.andP;  With this much initial support, weexpect it to receive early acceptance.andM;Motif on Apollo.andP;  In a related development, Hewlett-Packard announced thathas added the OSF graphical environment to its Apollo workstations, runningon top of the Domain operating system.andP;  HP was already shipping OSF/Motif forits own Unix workstations.andP;  Now, the two lines share one consistent graphicenvironment.andM;A single-node license of the Domain version of OSF/Motif is $550.andO;Multiple-node licenses include substantial discounts.andO;</TEXT></DOC>